# Contributing to the StockManagement Project

Thank you for your interest in contributing to the StockManagement project! This guide outlines the process for contributing to the project and the standards we expect from our contributors.

## How to Contribute

1. Fork the repository to your own GitHub account.
2. Create a new branch in your forked repository for the changes you want to make.
3. Make your changes to the codebase, and ensure that your code is clean and well-documented.
4. Test your changes thoroughly to ensure that they do not introduce any new bugs.
5. Submit a pull request from your branch to the main branch of the StockManagement repository.
6. Wait for the project maintainers to review your changes and provide feedback.

## Guidelines for Contributing

- Keep your changes focused and limited to one issue or feature at a time.
- Follow the coding style and formatting conventions used in the project.
- Write clear and concise commit messages that describe the changes you have made.
- Use descriptive and specific titles for your pull requests and issues.
- Provide clear and detailed explanations for your changes and the rationale behind them.
- Be open to feedback and willing to make changes to your code as needed.

## Reporting Issues

If you encounter a bug or issue with the StockManagement software, please report it using the GitHub Issues feature. When reporting an issue, please provide a clear and descriptive title, a detailed description of the problem, and any relevant information or screenshots that can help to diagnose the issue.

## Code of Conduct

We expect all contributors to follow the Code of Conduct outlined in the CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md file. We take this code seriously and will not tolerate any behavior that violates it.

Thank you for your contributions to the StockManagement project! Together, we can create a powerful tool for managing stock and inventory.
